To add this code to a Chrome extension, you will need to create a new Chrome extension and include the code in one of the extension's files. Here are the steps you can follow:

1. Create a new folder for your extension.
2. Create a file called `manifest.json` in the root of the folder, and add the following content to it:
```
{
  "manifest_version": 2,
  "name": "My Extension",
  "version": "1.0",
  "background": {
    "scripts": ["background.js"]
  },
  "permissions": ["https://www.youtube.com/*"],
  "browser_action": {
    "default_popup": "popup.html"
  }
}
```
This file is the manifest for your extension, and it specifies the extension's name, version, and other details. It also specifies the background script (`background.js`) that will run in the background and the permissions the extension needs (in this case, access to YouTube).

1. Create a file called `background.js` in the root of the folder, and add the code for downloading the YouTube video to it:
```
function downloadVideo(url, fileName) {
  // Import the pytube library
  const pytube = import('https://unpkg.com/pytube@9.6.4/dist/index.min.js');

  pytube.then(pytube => {
    // Create a YouTube object
    const yt = new pytube.YouTube(url);

    // Select the highest resolution video stream
    const videoStream = yt.streams
      .filter(s => s.type === 'video' && s.itag.includes('mp4'))
      .sort((a, b) => b.resolution - a.resolution)[0];

    // Download the video
    videoStream.download(fileName);
  });
}
```
This function takes the `url` and `fileName` as arguments and uses the `pytube` library to download the highest resolution video stream with the file extension `mp4` for the YouTube video specified in the `url` variable, and save it to a file with the name specified in the `fileName` variable in the default download directory.

1. Create a file called `popup.html` in the root of the folder, and add a form with a text input and a submit button to it:
```
<form>
  <label for="file-name">File name:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="file-name" name="file-name"><br>
  <input type="submit" value="Download">
</form>
```
This form will allow the user to enter the file name for the downloaded video.

1. Create a file called `popup.js` in the root of the folder, and add the following code to it:
```
// Get the form element
const form = document.querySelector('form');

// Add a submit event listener to the form
form.addEventListener('submit', event => {
  // Prevent the default form submission behavior
  event.preventDefault();

  // Get the file name from the form
  const fileName = document.querySelector('#file-name').value;
```
